snippet.title: Take a Tour of LA’s “Beyond the Streets” With Curator Roger Gastman
snippet.description:
Roger Gastman follows up his 2011 show at the MOCA in Los Angeles, “Art in the Streets,” with a new exhibition that touts itself as the biggest street art show ever.

Titled “Beyond the Streets,” the exhibition builds upon Gastman’s previous effort with 40,000+ sq ft of industrial indoor and outdoor space – including a full-size, playable handball court and historical recreation of the Venice Pavilion by adidas Skateboarding.

Artists participating in the exhibition include André Saraiva, Barry McGee, DABSMYLA, Dennis Hopper, FUTURA 2000, Jean-Michel Basquiat, Keith Haring, POSE, RETNA, REVOK, RIME, Shepard Fairey, Takashi Murakami, and 100+ others.

Enjoy a tour of the massive show from Gastman above and make sure to drop by from now until July 6. Head here to purchase advanced tickets. https://www.beyondthestreets.com/

snippet.title: Sangiev | Best Dressed YouTuber Lightweight Category
snippet.description:
Dropping out from Central Saint Martins (the one Ye’ famously couldn’t get into) in 2015, I decided textbook learning wasn’t for me. I saw a gap on YouTube for content I could relate to. The gap found a balance between high end ‘designer’ and streetwear. I felt if you wanted to watch videos on high-end fashion, you’d often end up on a major publication like Mr. Porter or GQ, whereas if you looked at streetwear, there were some great personalities delivering sick content, and it felt personal. I wanted to bring that energy to the high-end fashion scene with my own spin of vintage & formalwear. Two years later I recently packed in my part-time job and am now a full-time fashion content creator and menswear stylist.

snippet.title: Counterfeit Culture Moscow: Inside the Russian Fashion Black Market
snippet.description:
For the second installment of Counterfeit Culture, Highsnobiety’s first-ever documentary series, we headed to Moscow to find what’s driving Russia’s thriving market for fake streetwear. Russia’s counterfeit industry stretches back decades, to when Communism isolated the country from Western products. Now, almost 30 years after the collapse of the Soviet Union, Russia’s borders are open, but a fragile economy, international sanctions and low wages has kept the country’s demand for fakes alive and well.

Hennessy continues to push boundaries in the spirit of its Never stop. Never settle. mantra with a new collaboration from Harlem hip-hop artist and painter A$AP Ferg. Bringing together three of the artist’s passions: art, music and Cognac, this is Hennessy’s latest creative collaboration centered around the notion of pushing the limits of one’s potential. 

From humble beginnings in Harlem to his rise within hip hop collective A$AP Mob, Ferg shares his unique creative process, his passion for painting, and talks about his new collaborative track with Hennessy, titled “Family” - which features artwork painted by Ferg himself.

The Hennessy Uptown Inspired by A$AP Ferg Cocktail Kit ($78) includes ingredients to make eight Ferg-inspired cocktails and is now available for purchase at CocktailCourier.com. 

To create the Hennessy Uptown at home, combine the following ingredients in a shaker over ice until chilled: 1.5 oz. Hennessy V.S.O.P Privilège, .25 oz. cinnamon syrup, 3 oz. hibiscus tea and 3 dashes Angostura bitters. Strain over ice into a Collins glass and garnish with a lemon wheel, a pinch of chipotle powder and a float of crème de cassis.

snippet.title: Rip Hamilton Checks Out Gerard Starkey's Incredible Air Jordan Collection
snippet.description:
When the NBA comes to London it’s a coming together of sports, music and style, with transatlantic guests sampling the best that London has to offer. Three-time All-Star, former teammate of Michael Jordan and renowned sneakerhead Rip Hamilton was in town for the game and took the opportunity to visit a fellow Jordan obsessive.

London-based collector Gerard Starkey’s stunning collection of Jordans includes a haul of signed, game-worn Player Exclusives – an unrivalled treasure trove that even includes the Air Jordan XI worn by Jordan in Space Jam.

However, it was Gerard’s Air Jordan III collection that caught Rip’s eye. Boasting three signed Player Edition pairs – the White/Infra Red, the White/True Blue and the White Cement – Gerard and Rip bonded over a mutual admiration for the iconic silhouette, reminiscing over its place in NBA Slam Dunk Contest history.

Rip sealed a new friendship by gifting Gerard with a box-fresh pair of Black Cement Air Jordan III, a colourway that had previously eluded Gerard.

snippet.title: Vetements’ Hong Kong Pop-Up Featured Their Most Ridiculous Products Yet
snippet.description:
As a follow-up to previous flash sale events in Seoul and Los Angeles, Vetements hosted a one-day pop-up event at Hong Kong’s Kai Tak Cruise Terminal yesterday, offering a new selection of tongue-in-cheek accessories and clothing.

Inspired by the brand’s re-location from Paris to the Swiss city of Zürich, the new pop-up featured a range of Alpine tourist memorabilia including mugs (approx. $80 USD),  fridge magnets (approx. $25 USD) and souvenir dishes, taking the concept from their colette pop-up (which also included mugs and ridiculous accessories like sleeping masks) even further. DHL was also an official partner for the event, providing DHL vans and even staff to lend a hand.

Collaborative items were on hand in limited amounts, ranging from co-branded Umbro, Tommy Hilfiger and DHL apparel to Vetements’ latest sock-sneaker alongside Reebok. Select installations were also provided by Ladies’ Market on Tung Choi Street, the Hong Kong street market where haggling is encouraged.

See more here: https://www.highsnobiety.com/p/vetements-hong-kong-pop/

snippet.title: Counterfeit Culture | Seoul: A Look Inside Korea’s Fake Fashion World
snippet.description:
Part II Counterfeit Culture Moscow https://youtu.be/MwJTT1D2PbE

In recent years, Korea has emerged as one of the world’s fastest-growing fashion markets. Koreans are obsessed with fashion, and the country produces scores of talented designers, many of whom are now breaking out onto the global stage.



Beneath the surface, though, there’s an insane market for counterfeit streetwear. Of course, you can find fake clothing all over the globe, but there’s places in Seoul that are selling convincing knock-offs of hyped brands like Raf Simons, Off-White, Balenciaga and Fear Of God.
